Strategies for Finding Answers to Accessibility Issues

Finding an Answer to a Problem Demo

In this lesson, we’ll look at a real-world approach for finding solutions when faced with accessibility issues.

Searching the Web for Help

Developers are predisposed to searching StackOverflow for answers to code-related issues but should be cautious when it comes to accessibility specifics. It may or may not be a good place to find an example.

A recommended resource for cross-referencing ideas and solutions is the WebAIM mailing list.

Whatever the information source, you need to be discerning in what you take in. You also need to be diligent in testing and validating a proposed solution to ensure that what you found actually solves a user-impacting problem.

The CampSpots Checkout Process

Let’s examine the CampSpots checkout process, which contains several intentional accessibility problems. You can access the CampSpots checkout in the local dev server or on the deployed site.

The checkout page contains two levels of subscriptions that people can opt into, either of which will open a modal dialog when clicked.

Inside the modal, the radio buttons have a keyboard access issue.

The custom text field associated with the last radio button steals focus and removes the current selection from any other radio button. There is also no visible outline to indicate where focus is.

🛠️ Challenge: Finding an Answer to a Problem

Your challenge is to search the web for resources to inform a possible solution to the radio button issue on the checkout modal.

Spend no more than 10 minutes trying to find answers that can help you formulate a possible solution.

You don’t necessarily need to test and implement the solution!

Hint: The search terms “radio text input steals focus” is a good start.

🛠️ Solution: Finding an Answer to a Problem

In the solution video below, you will find commentary for potential solutions to the focus issue.

As you search for answers, think critically about what you find.

Fixes could happen on the development or design side of things, so try to keep you options open as you’re exploring.

Searching for answers is a learned skill and there is no perfect recipe. In fact, issues can have very different constraints and outcomes–some may be extremely difficult to search by keyword, until you find the best search criteria! As you gain more experience, you will develop your favorite resources and go-to processes to try and find solutions.
